{"key":"post-13097495","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>13097495</id>\n<content>&lt;/font&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;small&quot;&gt;Quote:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;mad capper said:&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;does it make any difference if you pre pour or does that not have any relevance? &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;post&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;I strongly advise against this.&amp;nbsp; Instead of one vector of contamination, you now have many.&amp;nbsp; In addition, agar tends to foam as it boils, and it can easily boil over in a petri dish, spilling out.&amp;nbsp; Now you have an ugly trail of agar on the outside of the dish for contaminants to use to get inside, much like the fuse on a firecracker.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;If you're using glass petri dishes, slip them into an autoclave bag or tyvek sleeve, so they can remain sterile when you remove them from the PC.&amp;nbsp; Sterilize agar in a whiskey bottle, using a hole in the lid and a piece of tyvek under the lid.&amp;nbsp; Pour in front of a flow hood, or as a second choice, a glovebox.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;I've never had the sugars caramelize in a PC at 15 psi.&amp;nbsp; I do a lot of cooking and sugars simply need to be hotter than 250F/120C for that to happen.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>13097668</next>\n<prev>13097432</prev>\n<first>13096274</first>\n<last>28138901</last>\n<when>1282703946</when>\n<utime>08/25/10 05:39 AM</utime>\n</post>"}